# Filter vs Interceptor in Spring Boot

## Key Difference

| Filter                                 | Interceptor                               |
| -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| Part of Servlet API                    | Part of Spring MVC                        |
| Executes before DispatcherServlet      | Executes after DispatcherServlet          |
| Can modify Request/Response            | Mainly handles request processing         |
| Used for Authentication, CORS, Logging | Used for Authorization, Auditing, Logging |

---

## Request Flow

```text
Client Request
      |
      v
Filter
      |
      v
DispatcherServlet
      |
      v
Interceptor
      |
      v
Controller
      |
      v
Interceptor
      |
      v
Response
```

---

## Filter

### Purpose

Used for:

* Authentication
* JWT Validation
* CORS
* Request/Response Logging

### Example

```java
@Component
public class LoggingFilter implements Filter {

    @Override
    public void doFilter(
            ServletRequest request,
            ServletResponse response,
            FilterChain chain)
            throws IOException, ServletException {

        System.out.println("Before Request");

        chain.doFilter(request, response);

        System.out.println("After Response");
    }
}
```

---

## Interceptor

### Purpose

Used for:

* Authorization
* Audit Logging
* Performance Monitoring
* Controller-specific Logic

### Example

```java
@Component
public class LoggingInterceptor
        implements HandlerInterceptor {

    @Override
    public boolean preHandle(
            HttpServletRequest request,
            HttpServletResponse response,
            Object handler) {

        System.out.println("Before Controller");
        return true;
    }
}
```

---

## Interceptor Lifecycle

### preHandle()

Runs before Controller.

```java
public boolean preHandle(...)
```

### postHandle()

Runs after Controller execution.

```java
public void postHandle(...)
```

### afterCompletion()

Runs after response is sent.

```java
public void afterCompletion(...)
```

---

## Why Spring Security Uses Filters?

Authentication must happen before Spring MVC.

```text
Request
   |
Security Filter Chain
   |
DispatcherServlet
   |
Controller
```

If authentication fails:

```text
401 Unauthorized
```

Controller is never reached.

---

## When to Use?

### Use Filter

* JWT Authentication
* CORS
* Compression
* Request/Response Modification
* Global Logging

### Use Interceptor

* Authorization
* Audit Logging
* Performance Monitoring
* Controller-level Validation

---

## Interview One-Liner

> Filter works at the Servlet container level and executes before Spring MVC, making it suitable for authentication and request/response processing. Interceptor works at the Spring MVC level and executes before and after controller execution, making it suitable for authorization, logging, and auditing.
